# OrderFlow — Architecture

> 4 microservices, **saga orchestration** (not choreography). Saga logic lives only in
> order-service as a durable state machine. Services communicate **only via Kafka**;
> never direct calls. One Postgres, four schemas, strict isolation.

## 1. System topology

```
                    ┌──────────────────────────────────────────┐
   React dashboard  │            order-service                  │
   ──SSE◄───────────┤  REST API · SSE · Saga orchestrator       │
   ──POST /orders──►│  state machine · Outbox + relay poller    │
                    └───┬───────────────▲──────────────────────┘
                        │ commands       │ result events
                        ▼ (Kafka)        │ (Kafka)
        ┌───────────────┬───────────────┬───────────────┐
        ▼               ▼               ▼
  inventory-service  payment-service  shipment-service
  reserve/release    capture/refund   create/cancel + mock carrier
        │               │               │  (Resilience4j CB)
        └──── all four share ONE Postgres, separate schemas ─────┘
        order │ inventory │ payment │ shipment   (per-service DB user)

Infra: Postgres · Kafka (KRaft) · Redis · Zipkin · Prometheus · Grafana  (Docker Compose)
```

- **order-service** = orchestrator: owns saga state machine, drives step sequence, triggers
  compensations in reverse order, exposes order API + SSE, runs the outbox relay.
- **inventory/payment/shipment** = participants: consume their commands, do one concern,
  publish result events. They contain **no saga logic**.

## 2. Backend — Clean Architecture layers (per service)

Each service is a Maven module with the same layered shape. Dependencies point **inward**
only (Infrastructure → Adapters → Use Cases → Entities).

| Layer | Contains | OrderFlow examples | .NET analogy |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Entities (domain)** | Pure domain types + invariants. No framework imports. | Saga sealed interface + state records, `Order`, `InventoryItem`, money/qty value objects, domain events (records) | POCOs / domain model, no EF/ASP.NET refs |
| **Use Cases (application)** | Business logic + transaction boundaries. Uses repositories directly; a couple of thin interfaces where they aid testing (`CommandPublisher`, `SagaLock`). | `PlaceOrderService`, `SagaOrchestrator`, `ReserveInventoryService` | Application/service layer |
| **Interface Adapters** | Controllers, Kafka listeners, DTOs + mappers, Spring Data repositories, presenters (SSE) | `OrderController`, `*KafkaListener`, `*Request/*Response` records, `OrderRepository`, `SseOrderPresenter` | Controllers, mappers, EF repositories |
| **Infrastructure** | Frameworks/drivers config: Spring config, Kafka/Redis/JPA wiring, Flyway, Resilience4j config, OTel | `KafkaConfig`, `RedisConfig`, `Resilience4jConfig`, Flyway migrations, `application.yml` | `Program.cs`/DI registration, provider config |

**Boundary rules (enforced by `reviewer.mdc`):**
- No business logic in controllers/listeners — they map + delegate to a service/use case.
- No DB access outside the repository layer.
- DTOs validated at the boundary (controller), never inside services.
- Domain types stay free of web/Kafka concerns.

**Persistence (idiomatic Spring, beginner-friendly):**
- One interface per aggregate: `OrderRepository extends JpaRepository<OrderEntity, UUID>` —
  Spring Data **auto-implements** it. No `Impl` class, no adapter, no hidden interface.
- Name is tech-neutral (`OrderRepository`, not `JpaOrderRepository`); swapping persistence
  later means editing this one interface. Pragmatic over pure — readability first.
- Custom queries via derived method names (`findByOrderId`) or `@Query` when needed.

### Key Spring idioms (with .NET equivalents)
- **Constructor injection** for all dependencies (no field `@Autowired`). ≈ ctor injection in .NET DI.
- **`@Transactional`** marks the use-case transaction boundary. ≈ `TransactionScope` / a single `SaveChanges`. Outbox row + state change share one `@Transactional` method.
- **Spring Data JPA repositories** (interfaces, auto-implemented). ≈ EF Core `DbContext` + repository.
- **`@KafkaListener`** = a consumer method. ≈ a `BackgroundService` Confluent consumer loop.
- **`@Scheduled`** for the outbox relay. ≈ `BackgroundService` + `PeriodicTimer`.
- **Records** for DTOs/events = immutable data carriers. ≈ C# `record`.
- **Sealed interface** for saga state = closed type hierarchy. ≈ closed class hierarchy / DU-style.

