## 8. Concurrency & reliability (what is actually implemented + known gaps)

**Implemented:**
- **Messaging delivery = at-least-once.** Kafka commands/events may be redelivered;
  **all consumers are idempotent** (F-04/05/08/10), keyed by `(orderId[,sku])`, so
  redelivery is safe. We do **not** rely on exactly-once semantics.
- **Outbox pattern (F-07):** state change + outbox row in one `@Transactional`. A
  **scheduled relay poller** publishes unsent rows (at-least-once) and marks them sent.
  Survives a crash between commit and publish.
- **Multi-instance outbox relay:** `SELECT … FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED` so concurrent relays
  grab disjoint batches; duplicates are harmless because consumers are idempotent.
- **Saga transition guarding:** **Redis distributed lock** per `orderId` around a transition
  **+ Postgres optimistic locking** (`@Version` column on the saga row). The DB version is
  the real safety net; the Redis lock reduces contention/wasted work.
- **Saga state durability:** Postgres is the **system of record** (`saga_instance` +
  `saga_step` audit). Redis holds only idempotency keys + transient locks.
- **Compensation:** orchestrator issues compensating commands in **reverse** completed-step
  order; each compensation is idempotent (a retried release/refund/cancel is a no-op).
- **Circuit breaker (F-11):** Resilience4j around the mock carrier (timeout + breaker; retry
  optional). Open breaker → fast-fail → saga compensates. ≈ Polly circuit breaker.
- **Kafka scaling:** per-service **consumer groups**; partitions key by `orderId` so all
  events for one order keep per-partition ordering and hit the same consumer.
- **Virtual threads (Java 21):** used for SSE connection handling and any orchestrator
  fan-out/waits to cheaply hold many concurrent I/O-bound tasks. ≈ closer to async/await
  ergonomics than raw threads.

**Known gaps (documented, not hidden):**
- **No saga timeout/stuck-saga sweeper** in v1 — a participant that never replies leaves a
  saga in-progress. Timestamps + correlationId are persisted so a sweeper can be added
  later (extensible). Documented as a gap.
- **Single Postgres instance** = shared infra blast radius (vs true DB-per-service). Logical
  isolation only (schema + per-service user). Conscious trade-off for the demo.
- **Virtual threads don't make blocking JPA/Kafka non-blocking** — they help concurrency, not
  raw latency. Noted so it isn't oversold.
- **SSE multi-instance fan-out** not built in v1 (single order-service instance). Scale-up
  path: each instance consumes the saga-events topic (or Redis pub/sub) to fan out to its
  local SSE clients. Documented.
- **Exactly-once not attempted** — at-least-once + idempotency is the deliberate posture.

## 9. Kafka topic & schema conventions
- Topics: `orderflow.commands.<service>` (e.g. `orderflow.commands.inventory`) and
  `orderflow.events.<service>` (results). Orchestrator publishes commands, consumes events.
- Message envelope (record): `{ correlationId(orderId), sagaId, type, occurredAt, payload }`
  + W3C `traceparent` in Kafka headers.
- Keyed by `orderId` for partition-ordering.
- Versioning: additive fields only in v1; consumers tolerate unknown fields.

## 10. Tech mapping summary (Spring/Java ⇄ .NET)
| Concern | OrderFlow (Java/Spring) | .NET equivalent |
|---|---|---|
| Resilience | Resilience4j | Polly |
| ORM / migrations | Spring Data JPA + Hibernate / Flyway | EF Core / EF Migrations or DbUp |
| Tx boundary | `@Transactional` | `TransactionScope` / `SaveChanges` |
| Background work | `@Scheduled`, `@KafkaListener` | `BackgroundService`, hosted consumers |
| Metrics/tracing | Micrometer + OTel | `System.Diagnostics` + OTel .NET |
| Web host | Spring Boot embedded Tomcat/Netty | ASP.NET Core / Kestrel |
| DI | Spring context, ctor injection | built-in `IServiceCollection` |
| Outbox | hand-rolled + relay poller | MassTransit outbox / hand-rolled |
